  "prompt": "3. Who decides who will manage the company and how?",
  "response": "Here's a comprehensive overview of how management is typically determined in a company:\n\n1. Ownership Structure\n- In small businesses, owners often manage directly\n- Larger companies usually separate ownership from management\n- Shareholders elect board members who then hire executives\n\n2. Board of Directors\n- Elected by shareholders\n- Responsible for:\n- Selecting/hiring the CEO\n- Setting overall company strategy\n- Overseeing executive performance\n- Representing shareholders' interests\n\n3. Executive Leadership Selection\n- Board of Directors typically selects the CEO\n- CEO then helps select other top executives (COO, CFO, etc.)\n- Selection based on:\n- Professional qualifications\n- Leadership experience\n- Strategic vision\n- Track record of success\n\n4. Corporate Governance Models\n- Different models exist:\n- Traditional hierarchical structure\n- Flat organizational structure\n- Matrix management\n- Collaborative leadership\n\n5. Factors Influencing Management Selection\n- Company size\n- Industry standards\n- Ownership type (public/private)\n- Legal requirements\n- Company culture\n- Performance metrics\n\n6. Additional Selection Methods\n- Internal promotions\n- External recruitment\n- Succession planning\n- Performance-based advancement\n\nThe specific approach varies depending on the company's unique characteristics and governance structure.",
